		<td><b>What type of 40 pin IC socket comes with CopyNES USB?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Does anyone know the type of socket that retroUsb includes in their copyNES USB kits? 
<br />
<br />I've been working on installing copyNES. Because I am new to desoldering, I ruined the 2A03 on the NES I was modding. I also accidentally broke the IC socket that came in the copyNES kit &gt;&lt;
<br />
<br />So I ordered a replacement 2A03 here:
<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.mikesarcade.com/cgi-bin/store.pl">http://www.mikesarcade.com/cgi-bin/store.pl</a><!-- m --> (search "2A03"). 
<br />
<br />And then I bought a standard 40-pin socket at Rat Shack. 
<br />I soldered the new socket onto the NES motherboard and then plugged in my new 2A03. I popped in Monster Party and it worked perfectly! 
<br />
<br />Next I removed the 2A03 from the NES and moved it to the copyNES board. I then pushed the copyNES board into the socket of the NES motherboard. I pushed really hard, literally until I drew blood on my thumb. 
<br />The copyNES did not fit into the socket. It does not fit into the socket. 
<br />
<br />Apparently I need to get the EXACT socket that came with the copyNES. That or solder each pin of the CopyNES-NES connector by hand. I'm not too interested in that second method. It's bit cludgey and I hesitate even as a last  resort.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


